description: From Middle English launde, from Old French launde (“wooded area”) (French lande), of Germanic or Gaulish origin, from Proto-Germanic *landą (“land”) or Proto-Celtic *landā, both from Proto-Indo-European *lendʰ- (“land, heath”). Doublet of land.

entries.meaning: (archaic) A grassy plain or pasture, especially surrounded by woodland; a glade.
examples: About them lay long launds of green grass dappled with celandine and anemones,
